## 

<span key="04b7ae7e8e074783be0855f33cd7551f"><span offset-key="04b7ae7e8e074783be0855f33cd7551f:0">Here’s part one for reference:</span></span>

<span key="4964536433d241d6baf2196c229aa96c"><span offset-key="4964536433d241d6baf2196c229aa96c:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">​</span></span></span><a href="https://bryanguner.medium.com/the-web-developers-technical-interview-e347d7db3822" class="css-4rbku5 css-1dbjc4n r-1loqt21 r-1471scf r-1otgn73 r-1i6wzkk r-lrvibr"><span data-key="6732a980467b4006a5aa61eae12e2b67" data-rnw-int-class="nearest_257-2027_259-2028-237__"><span data-key="54e0a321b938460db555a1df529c2f53"><strong>The Web Developer’s Technical Interview</strong><span data-offset-key="54e0a321b938460db555a1df529c2f53:1"> </span><em>Questions….Answers… and links to the missing pieces.</em><span data-offset-key="54e0a321b938460db555a1df529c2f53:3">bryanguner.medium.com</span></span></span></a><span key="2ac508b70622418db2481e7a3b5f02fa"><span offset-key="2ac508b70622418db2481e7a3b5f02fa:0"><span slate-zero-width="z">​</span></span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="444dfdee70be4ceb97360697ee73df7d">**­­­­If you were to describe semantic HTML to the next cohort of students, what would you say?**</span>

<span key="7d9f09781cf740cea0ff739ffb925103"><span offset-key="7d9f09781cf740cea0ff739ffb925103:0">Semantic HTML is markup that conveys meaning, not appearance, to search engines to make everything easier to identify.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="19f8e6788ed74d07b471775464b3e456">**Name two big differences between display: block; and display: inline;.**</span>

<span key="19544706b1364d9d819cdc33f15d2039"><span offset-key="19544706b1364d9d819cdc33f15d2039:0">block starts on a new line and takes up the full width of the content. inline starts on the same line as previous content, in line with other content, and takes up only the space needed for the content.</span></span>

<span key="4076eb8da1fd475abca9dfb3699f6798"><span offset-key="4076eb8da1fd475abca9dfb3699f6798:0">· </span>**What are the 4 areas of the box model?**</span>

<span key="903bee32c0ce49b5a584b7cbe416167b"><span offset-key="903bee32c0ce49b5a584b7cbe416167b:0">content, padding, border, margin</span></span>

<span key="64f93d3ffe724e9088439ed6a4984ac6"><span offset-key="64f93d3ffe724e9088439ed6a4984ac6:0">· </span>**While using flexbox, what axis does the following property work on: align-items: center?**</span>

<span key="6ea2a19a5c7a4f7f996075d81b55ed0c"><span offset-key="6ea2a19a5c7a4f7f996075d81b55ed0c:0">cross-axis</span></span>

<span key="baa0f580520e4bae8fbdee4e420d3b40"><span offset-key="baa0f580520e4bae8fbdee4e420d3b40:0">· </span>**Explain why git is valuable to a team of developers.**</span>

<span key="a75bc1ea97384bdb9336ecbd05af61df"><span offset-key="a75bc1ea97384bdb9336ecbd05af61df:0">Allows you to dole out tiny pieces of a large project to many developers who can all work towards the same goal on their own chunks, allows roll back if you make a mistake; version control.</span></span>

<span key="7777a52b44b54bad9e73a1ce45f3ab93"><span offset-key="7777a52b44b54bad9e73a1ce45f3ab93:0">· </span>**What is the difference between an adaptive website and a fully responsive website?**</span>

<span key="254c934ce5f647d8a78306d0e79c41b1"><span offset-key="254c934ce5f647d8a78306d0e79c41b1:0">An adaptive website “adapts” to fit a pre-determined set of screen sizes/devices, and a responsive one changes to fit all devices.</span></span>

<span key="416adc1ef74d4bac840bbae6a7df0169"><span offset-key="416adc1ef74d4bac840bbae6a7df0169:0">· </span>**Describe what it means to be mobile first vs desktop first.**</span>

<span key="f065c2ffd931427993515d4181ca2214"><span offset-key="f065c2ffd931427993515d4181ca2214:0">It means you develop/code the site with mobile in mind first and work your way outward in screen size.</span></span>

<span key="a3c6384be9c74f1eaaddf9529cf95071"><span offset-key="a3c6384be9c74f1eaaddf9529cf95071:0">· </span>**What does font-size: 62.5% in the html tag do for us when using rem units?**</span>

<span key="2f8136bcf162407e93a3ca0a9742bf2a"><span offset-key="2f8136bcf162407e93a3ca0a9742bf2a:0">This setting makes it so that 1 rem = 10 px for font size, easier to calculate.</span></span>

<span key="3048ab8cbe924b9fb011d1c0bab29404"><span offset-key="3048ab8cbe924b9fb011d1c0bab29404:0">· </span>**How would you describe preprocessing to someone new to CSS?**</span>

<span key="2c841f22f9f2414889a6cf2e81f655ff"><span offset-key="2c841f22f9f2414889a6cf2e81f655ff:0">Preprocessing is basically a bunch of functions and variables you can use to store CSS settings in different ways that make it easier to code CSS.</span></span>

<span key="000fce5b20d24213bf64d3ea35351ff1"><span offset-key="000fce5b20d24213bf64d3ea35351ff1:0">· </span>**What is your favorite concept in preprocessing? What is the concept that gives you the most trouble?**</span>

<span key="093e200aae26491a8ff15ed49d03072b"><span offset-key="093e200aae26491a8ff15ed49d03072b:0">Favorite is (parametric) mixins; but I don’t have a lot of trouble with preprocessing. What gives me the most trouble is knowing ahead of time what would be good to go in a mixin for a given site.</span></span>

<span key="de96cc57a9ce40efa9e9c1ce847df874"><span offset-key="de96cc57a9ce40efa9e9c1ce847df874:0">· </span>**Describe the biggest difference between .forEach & .map.**</span>

<span key="6c8ab96296154077a2133a50082aedc1"><span offset-key="6c8ab96296154077a2133a50082aedc1:0">forEach iterates over an array item by item, and map calls a function on each array item, but returns another/additional array, unlike forEach.</span></span>

<span key="22f108d18fed43a78a6d82673f4b30f4"><span offset-key="22f108d18fed43a78a6d82673f4b30f4:0">· </span>**What is the difference between a function and a method?**</span>

<span key="d463a04966d243879bd997386ac25ff1"><span offset-key="d463a04966d243879bd997386ac25ff1:0">Every function is an object. If a value is a function, it is a method. Methods have to be ‘received’ by something; functions do not.</span></span>

<span key="42e9ac3212f4482bb42cca4f1483eced"><span offset-key="42e9ac3212f4482bb42cca4f1483eced:0">· </span>**What is closure?**</span>

<span key="b563d84904514cf7bee205c9636e830e"><span offset-key="b563d84904514cf7bee205c9636e830e:0">It is code identified elsewhere that we can use later; gives the ability to put functions together. If a variable isn’t defined, a function looks outward for context.</span></span>

<span key="8f0df89cb1714acaa16c4e81fedc3a6a"><span offset-key="8f0df89cb1714acaa16c4e81fedc3a6a:0">· </span>**Describe the four rules of the ‘this’ keyword.**</span>

1.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">1.</span>
    <span key="08af59763aeb4039aa9d87be35585615"><span offset-key="08af59763aeb4039aa9d87be35585615:0">Window/global binding — this is the window/console object. ‘use strict’; to prevent window binding.</span></span>

2.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">2.</span>
    <span key="cef886523d1448518ffc80022c658806"><span offset-key="cef886523d1448518ffc80022c658806:0">Implicit binding — when a function is called by a dot, the object preceding the dot is the ‘this’. 80 percent of ‘this’ is from this type of binding.</span></span>

3.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">3.</span>
    <span key="bb5108aa416d4fb9b0d7fa057a4154af"><span offset-key="bb5108aa416d4fb9b0d7fa057a4154af:0">New binding — points to new object created & returned by constructor function</span></span>

4.  <span class="r-1awozwy r-1nf4jbm r-6koalj r-18u37iz r-gg6oyi r-ubezar r-16dba41 r-135wba7 r-1m04atk r-1pyaxff" contenteditable="false" style="height:24px">4.</span>
    <span key="b00d20f9e56341119cc79b2ac7796802"><span offset-key="b00d20f9e56341119cc79b2ac7796802:0">Explicit binding — whenever call, bind, or apply are used.</span></span>

<span key="c7fc9bd106624e90bc91410d3cc33c5f"><span offset-key="c7fc9bd106624e90bc91410d3cc33c5f:0">· </span>**Why do we need super() in an extended class?**</span>

<span key="39a92c43bdd84989a17f8ef058a73d65"><span offset-key="39a92c43bdd84989a17f8ef058a73d65:0">Super ties the parent to the child.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="5625a112327c458394232386edace628">**What is the DOM?**</span>

<span key="fd136b1c21a749cb80fc9417da8659cb"><span offset-key="fd136b1c21a749cb80fc9417da8659cb:0">Document object model, the ‘window’ or container that holds all the page’s elements</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="9637954d76ee4c4a88d334b10d210f33">**What is an event?**</span>

<span key="689f416c10404013a53db407ab57a145"><span offset-key="689f416c10404013a53db407ab57a145:0">An event is something happening on or to the page, like a mouse click, doubleclick, key up/down, pointer out of element/over element, things like this. There are tons of “events” that javascript can detect.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="5fd04f77a4e8472a856b1a7450db52b7">**What is an event listener?**</span>

<span key="dd488556b7c34adf872918d3a2aa6e35"><span offset-key="dd488556b7c34adf872918d3a2aa6e35:0">Javascript command that ‘listens’ for an event to happen on the page to a given element and then runs a function when that event happens</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="d8fc5419e715485892f0937120e05568">**Why would we convert a NodeList into an Array?**</span>

<span key="a01da143341f424ab70fcc1460970684"><span offset-key="a01da143341f424ab70fcc1460970684:0">A NodeList isn’t a real array, so it won’t have access to array methods such as slice or map.</span></span>

-   <img src="data:image/svg+xml;base64," class="r-1nf4jbm" />

    <span key="1c4ee39281ce4a7e9226a30c43fd33bf">**What is a component?**</span>

<span key="0893670c0da44a428e1d74bacc7a65b4"><span offset-key="0893670c0da44a428e1d74bacc7a65b4:0">Reusable pieces of code to display info in a consistent repeatable way</span></span>

<span key="6f81d7af14f842cf9123aa7b00242438"><span offset-key="6f81d7af14f842cf9123aa7b00242438:0">· </span>**What is React JS and what problems does it try and solve? Support your answer with concepts introduced in class and from your personal research on the web.**</span>

<span key="8e608bd372714022a53a41be4c27503a"><span offset-key="8e608bd372714022a53a41be4c27503a:0">ReactJS is a library used to build large applications. It’s very good at assisting developers in manipulating the DOM element to create rich user experiences. We need a way to off-load the state/data that our apps use, and React helps us do that.</span></span>

<span key="4ee516f1d6db4ac8b28502581276db8c"><span offset-key="4ee516f1d6db4ac8b28502581276db8c:0">· </span>**What does it mean to** ***think*** **in react?**</span>

<span key="189d01394f3749bf896a2b03a7fd2605"><span offset-key="189d01394f3749bf896a2b03a7fd2605:0">It makes you think about how to organize/build apps a little differently because it’s very scalable and allows you to build huge apps. React’s one-way data flow makes everything modular and fast. You can build apps top-down or bottom-up.</span></span>

<span key="e73831f26a5145f89195b9d90ab48b99"><span offset-key="e73831f26a5145f89195b9d90ab48b99:0">· </span>**Describe state.**</span>

<span key="cb7c67994b9c40099c6329a21a58c486"><span offset-key="cb7c67994b9c40099c6329a21a58c486:0">Some data we want to display.</span></span>

<span key="3fc696a8adc348aea035dce6a2385047"><span offset-key="3fc696a8adc348aea035dce6a2385047:0">· </span>**Describe props.**</span>

<span key="e33274be4e5448249cec9d82966e315a"><span offset-key="e33274be4e5448249cec9d82966e315a:0">Props are like function arguments in JS and attributes in HTML.</span></span>

<span key="99cb78076d9f4083a2df28cb99191f65"><span offset-key="99cb78076d9f4083a2df28cb99191f65:0">· </span>**What are side effects, and how do you sync effects in a React component to state or prop changes?**</span>

<span key="1aa24c4dd85f46fa93a96c295d866f1d"><span offset-key="1aa24c4dd85f46fa93a96c295d866f1d:0">Side effects are anything that affects something outside the executed function’s scope like fetching data from an API, a timer, or logging.</span></span>

<span key="ec04f237199541399d2d1be21cab80f4"><span offset-key="ec04f237199541399d2d1be21cab80f4:0">· </span>**Explain benefit(s) using client-side routing?**</span>

<span key="fa5d3a8d696f4691964ee5532c465394"><span offset-key="fa5d3a8d696f4691964ee5532c465394:0">Answer: It’s much more efficient than the traditional way, because a lot of data isn’t being transmitted unnecessarily.</span></span>

<span key="a9bf9fd58fb6403eae9705ad94a9d872"><span offset-key="a9bf9fd58fb6403eae9705ad94a9d872:0">· </span>**Why would you use class component over function components (removing hooks from the question)?**</span>

<span key="1e40ba76b9984ef58d5517ab1b4a9fa8"><span offset-key="1e40ba76b9984ef58d5517ab1b4a9fa8:0">Because some companies still use class components and don’t want to switch their millions of dollars’ worth of code over to all functional hooks, and also there’s currently a lot more troubleshooting content out there for classes that isn’t out there for hooks. Also, functional components are better when you don’t need state, presentational components.</span></span>

<span key="4f178649c29d4383bca74a94fc983e82"><span offset-key="4f178649c29d4383bca74a94fc983e82:0">· </span>**Name three lifecycle methods and their purposes.**</span>

<span key="763c10f5c9894599aa5599f42b1a9efe"><span offset-key="763c10f5c9894599aa5599f42b1a9efe:0">componentDidMount = do the stuff inside this ‘function’ after the component mounted</span></span>

<span key="da2962e122be43c399222b305446f8f9"><span offset-key="da2962e122be43c399222b305446f8f9:0">componentDidUpdate = do the stuff inside this function after the component updated</span></span>

<span key="79f4b712ec1146b289fe4ac6c5cacd4b"><span offset-key="79f4b712ec1146b289fe4ac6c5cacd4b:0">componentWillUnmount = clean-up in death/unmounting phase</span></span>

<span key="0ddc8c6d925e423a9019f32f55aefe6c"><span offset-key="0ddc8c6d925e423a9019f32f55aefe6c:0">· </span>**What is the purpose of a custom hook?**</span>

<span key="f08d282d74bb4ebbbcc37e9ed06c2636"><span offset-key="f08d282d74bb4ebbbcc37e9ed06c2636:0">allow you to apply non-visual behavior and stateful logic throughout your components by reusing the same hook over and over again</span></span>

<span key="72c858a5d074475eaac3565d5eac43b7"><span offset-key="72c858a5d074475eaac3565d5eac43b7:0">· </span>**Why is it important to test our apps?**</span>

<span key="cc3fb768c24149a49c8a1b8672e4c50e"><span offset-key="cc3fb768c24149a49c8a1b8672e4c50e:0">Gets bugs fixed faster, reduces regression risk, makes you consider/work out the edge cases, acts as documentation, acts as safety net when refactoring, makes code more trustworthy</span></span>

<span key="d38042093e3e44778e808a8e3ef8a6b6"><span offset-key="d38042093e3e44778e808a8e3ef8a6b6:0">· </span>**What problem does the context API help solve?**</span>

<span key="02cabcc1164649e8ad87d6581f999e1e"><span offset-key="02cabcc1164649e8ad87d6581f999e1e:0">You can store data in a context object instead of prop drilling.</span></span>

<span key="7f6484f128334f009801c5ba8917c400"><span offset-key="7f6484f128334f009801c5ba8917c400:0">· </span>**In your own words, describe actions, reducers and the store and their role in Redux. What does each piece do? Why is the store known as a ‘single source of truth’ in a redux application?**</span>

<span key="fd9d2444be1b4185b9a1569dc11e27c9"><span offset-key="fd9d2444be1b4185b9a1569dc11e27c9:0">Everything that changes within your app is represented by a single JS object called the store. The store contains state for our application. When changes are made to our application state, we never write to our store object but rather clone the state object, modify the clone, and replace the original state with the new copy, never mutating the original object. Reducers are the only place we can update our state. Actions tell our reducers “how” to update the state, and perhaps with what data it should be updated, but only a reducer can actually update the state.</span></span>

<span key="5e2aab6e22ac4012a1c4107d1c0cf2c8"><span offset-key="5e2aab6e22ac4012a1c4107d1c0cf2c8:0">· </span>**What is the difference between Application state and Component state? When would be a good time to use one over the other?**</span>

<span key="527e243ef44e41ecbdecf6a0dc1ab8d3"><span offset-key="527e243ef44e41ecbdecf6a0dc1ab8d3:0">App state is global, component state is local. Use component state when you have component-specific variables.</span></span>

<span key="42b70c5109c846db8bbce335ab361e3f"><span offset-key="42b70c5109c846db8bbce335ab361e3f:0">· </span>**Describe redux-thunk, what does it allow us to do? How does it change our action-creators?**</span>

<span key="ccbf6cbba871467fb2e70725177a2f27"><span offset-key="ccbf6cbba871467fb2e70725177a2f27:0">Redux Thunk is middleware that provides the ability to handle asynchronous operations inside our Action Creators, because reducers are normally synchronous.</span></span>

<span key="a883402acca24fea86c32226fac3896a"><span offset-key="a883402acca24fea86c32226fac3896a:0">· </span>**What is your favorite state management system you’ve learned and this sprint? Please explain why!**</span>

<span key="26d79a056bd849138719bb170d46c2e3"><span offset-key="26d79a056bd849138719bb170d46c2e3:0">Redux, because I felt it was easier to understand than the context API.</span></span>

<span key="a5e71f864e194a6a961f48b94e6908e9"><span offset-key="a5e71f864e194a6a961f48b94e6908e9:0">· </span>**Explain what a token is used for.**</span>

<span key="fa3189d9d5f14e6abb9e456532e4a7ea"><span offset-key="fa3189d9d5f14e6abb9e456532e4a7ea:0">Many services out in the wild require the client (our React app, for example) to provide proof that it’s authenticated with them. The server running these services can issue a JWT (JSON Web Token) as the authentication token, in exchange for correct login credentials.</span></span>

<span key="0e40a4c4389f47bea88b659130e26b60"><span offset-key="0e40a4c4389f47bea88b659130e26b60:0">· </span>**What steps can you take in your web apps to keep your data secure?**</span>

<span key="0720e18a6441442f82b573627b0dc075"><span offset-key="0720e18a6441442f82b573627b0dc075:0">As we build our web apps, we will most likely have some “protected” routes — routes that we only want to render if the user has logged in and been authenticated by our server. The way this normally works is we make a login request, sending the server the user’s username and password. The server will check those credentials against what is in the database, and if it can authenticate the user, it will return a token. Once we have this token, we can add two layers of protection to our app. One with protected routes, the other by sending an authentication header with our API calls (as we learned in the above objective).</span></span>

<span key="0328734418674bc6a8cc5823777a6a14"><span offset-key="0328734418674bc6a8cc5823777a6a14:0">· </span>**Describe how web servers work.**</span>

<span key="46798abded444939b881489c560a3168"><span offset-key="46798abded444939b881489c560a3168:0">The “world wide web” (which we’ll refer to as “the web”) is just a part of the internet — which is itself a network of interconnected computers. The web is just one way to share data over the internet. It consists of a body of information stored on web servers, ready to be shared across the world. The term “web server” can mean two things:</span></span>

<span key="50fe9c4ea81b40c8834a6f2e139599c2"><span offset-key="50fe9c4ea81b40c8834a6f2e139599c2:0">· a computer that stores the code for a website</span></span>

<span key="2cc1e06e3a1c4368ab663cbddfaa3c7a"><span offset-key="2cc1e06e3a1c4368ab663cbddfaa3c7a:0">· a program that runs on such a computer</span></span>

<span key="cea325e721c1416a8bf9c6ea103b536f"><span offset-key="cea325e721c1416a8bf9c6ea103b536f:0">The physical computer device that we call a web server is connected to the internet, and stores the code for different websites to be shared across the world at all times. When we load the code for our websites, or web apps, on a server like this, we would say that the server is “hosting” our website/app.</span></span>

<span key="2cdeb4d308a2453c974403f3ee06c21c"><span offset-key="2cdeb4d308a2453c974403f3ee06c21c:0">· </span>**Which HTTP methods can be mapped to the CRUD acronym that we use when interfacing with APIs/Servers.**</span>

<span key="f290f5e7fcc34558a5707bafa512172a"><span offset-key="f290f5e7fcc34558a5707bafa512172a:0">Create, Read, Update, Delete</span></span>

<span key="d75cd542b15e4baeb1b81ce31f81f396"><span offset-key="d75cd542b15e4baeb1b81ce31f81f396:0">· </span>**Mention two parts of Express that you learned about this week.**</span>

<span key="6f0866c5ec744e6097095831cecd3047"><span offset-key="6f0866c5ec744e6097095831cecd3047:0">Routing/router, Middleware, convenience helpers</span></span>

<span key="c297e636c3214999932c89bd5c159e10"><span offset-key="c297e636c3214999932c89bd5c159e10:0">· </span>**Describe Middleware?**</span>

<span key="03d36627a0ac441c8525b25b21806d9f"><span offset-key="03d36627a0ac441c8525b25b21806d9f:0">array of functions that get executed in the order they are introduced into the server code</span></span>

<span key="dac72e7e5faa4a75abb0cec2db4ddf32"><span offset-key="dac72e7e5faa4a75abb0cec2db4ddf32:0">· </span>**Describe a Resource?**</span>

<span key="df00b375973645aebbe53eeff6846420"><span offset-key="df00b375973645aebbe53eeff6846420:0">o everything is a </span>**resource**<span offset-key="df00b375973645aebbe53eeff6846420:2">.</span></span>

<span key="dde326defd6e431582f4517b00c97214"><span offset-key="dde326defd6e431582f4517b00c97214:0">o each resource is accessible via a </span>**unique URI**<span offset-key="dde326defd6e431582f4517b00c97214:2">.</span></span>

<span key="9653286cad17450aa68a1d24153b8e7a"><span offset-key="9653286cad17450aa68a1d24153b8e7a:0">o resources can have multiple </span>**representations**<span offset-key="9653286cad17450aa68a1d24153b8e7a:2">.</span></span>

<span key="b62968ec9d004805adc8453073bf5332"><span offset-key="b62968ec9d004805adc8453073bf5332:0">o communication is done over a </span>**stateless**<span offset-key="b62968ec9d004805adc8453073bf5332:2"> protocol (HTTP).</span></span>

<span key="831951ddae05461fb4c715623275db85"><span offset-key="831951ddae05461fb4c715623275db85:0">o management of resources is done via </span>**HTTP methods**<span offset-key="831951ddae05461fb4c715623275db85:2">.</span></span>

<span key="6ec8c93310a44a3eae6657f648e4ddaa"><span offset-key="6ec8c93310a44a3eae6657f648e4ddaa:0">· </span>**What can the API return to help clients know if a request was successful?**</span>

<span key="455315e1b22946d5810069491812f39d"><span offset-key="455315e1b22946d5810069491812f39d:0">200 status code/201 status code</span></span>

<span key="e0dfc93f85a343f5babf016c42d3cb66"><span offset-key="e0dfc93f85a343f5babf016c42d3cb66:0">· </span>**How can we partition our application into sub-applications?**</span>

<span key="4769c4de44be493885f51e48c473976c"><span offset-key="4769c4de44be493885f51e48c473976c:0">By dividing the code up into multiple files and ‘requiring’ them in the main server file.</span></span>

<span key="5cf3ceae2d474297bb7cb028dd41e8d8"><span offset-key="5cf3ceae2d474297bb7cb028dd41e8d8:0">· </span>**Explain the difference between Relational Databases and SQL.**</span>

<span key="789c7172bdf143a1a598ea0f4d88be64"><span offset-key="789c7172bdf143a1a598ea0f4d88be64:0">SQL is the language used to access a relational database.</span></span>

<span key="17f8b011fb164b6583955953309b9f20"><span offset-key="17f8b011fb164b6583955953309b9f20:0">· </span>**Why do tables need a primary key?**</span>

<span key="f6cd9fdcde7a48b5801350ec0ff3ffcf"><span offset-key="f6cd9fdcde7a48b5801350ec0ff3ffcf:0">To uniquely identify each record/row.</span></span>

<span key="ce1963285bd44b0fa5330449a47736e2"><span offset-key="ce1963285bd44b0fa5330449a47736e2:0">· </span>**What is the name given to a table column that references the primary key on another table.**</span>

<span key="f9020351653b4466bd6a61a84f03ba33"><span offset-key="f9020351653b4466bd6a61a84f03ba33:0">Foreign key</span></span>

<span key="a434c6293f1e44f28f525762a6518d8c"><span offset-key="a434c6293f1e44f28f525762a6518d8c:0">· </span>**What do we need in order to have a** ***many to many*** **relationship between two tables.**</span>

<span key="397752ad2324473ab9abac6335d2e4fb"><span offset-key="397752ad2324473ab9abac6335d2e4fb:0">An </span>**intermediary table**<span offset-key="397752ad2324473ab9abac6335d2e4fb:2"> that holds foreign keys that reference the primary key on the related tables.</span></span>

<span key="21bd19e1c2d14585bdde797c78747bfd"><span offset-key="21bd19e1c2d14585bdde797c78747bfd:0">· </span>**What is the purpose of using** ***sessions*?**</span>

<span key="04ad6fb9ee98473181230a2f139922d5"><span offset-key="04ad6fb9ee98473181230a2f139922d5:0">The purpose is to persist data across requests.</span></span>

<span key="0c195146b853454a94c74e54301093e5"><span offset-key="0c195146b853454a94c74e54301093e5:0">· </span>**What does bcrypt do to help us store passwords in a secure manner?**</span>

<span key="3a5be934f3634eb88915524aa29501c4"><span offset-key="3a5be934f3634eb88915524aa29501c4:0">o password hashing function.</span></span>

<span key="f65f0993525c415b8baf6bc3c58e22dd"><span offset-key="f65f0993525c415b8baf6bc3c58e22dd:0">o implements salting both manual and automatically.</span></span>

<span key="c3d4cda93f084c608d7f19a9ae420231"><span offset-key="c3d4cda93f084c608d7f19a9ae420231:0">o accumulative hashing rounds.</span></span>

<span key="a657c9dde80743fc8a143bf8a43e525a"><span offset-key="a657c9dde80743fc8a143bf8a43e525a:0">· </span>**What does bcrypt do to slow down attackers?**</span>

<span key="47e9c0c22ae749a19d7601abcc74eb6d"><span offset-key="47e9c0c22ae749a19d7601abcc74eb6d:0">Having an algorithm that hashes the information multiple times (rounds) means an attacker needs to have the hash, know the algorithm used, and how many rounds were used to generate the hash in the first place. So it basically makes it a lot more difficult to get somebody’s password.</span></span>

<span key="359c59e74c2449e1ac82a2df00240ab8"><span offset-key="359c59e74c2449e1ac82a2df00240ab8:0">· </span>**What are the three parts of the JSON Web Token?**</span>

<span key="5336965c69324e31bd5749d203c1b522"><span offset-key="5336965c69324e31bd5749d203c1b522:0">Header, payload, signature</span></span>
